<p>The <b>Bourne shell</b>, or <b>sh</b>, was the default <a href="/wiki/Unix_shell" title="Unix shell">Unix shell</a> of <a href="/wiki/Version_7_Unix" title="Version 7 Unix">Unix Version 7</a>, and replaced the <a href="/wiki/Thompson_shell" title="Thompson shell">Thompson shell</a>, whose executable file had the same name, <b>sh</b>. It was developed by <a href="/wiki/Stephen_Bourne" title="Stephen Bourne" class="mw-redirect">Stephen Bourne</a>, of <a href="/wiki/AT%26T" title="AT&amp;T">AT&amp;T</a> <a href="/wiki/Bell_Laboratories" title="Bell Laboratories" class="mw-redirect">Bell Laboratories</a>, and was released in 1977 in the <a href="/wiki/Version_7_Unix" title="Version 7 Unix">Version 7 Unix</a> release distributed to colleges and universities. It remains a popular default shell for Unix accounts. The <a href="/wiki/Executable" title="Executable">binary</a> program of the Bourne shell or a compatible program is located at <code>/bin/sh</code> on most <a href="/wiki/Unix" title="Unix">Unix</a> systems, and is still the default shell for the root <a href="/wiki/Superuser" title="Superuser">superuser</a> on many current Unix implementations.</p>
